	     <tr><td valign=top id=fs8 class=mform><span id=notbold>By:</span> <a href=poster.html?user=117530><span id=Guru>Calabar</span></a><br><b><span id=Guru>Guru</span></b><br><span id=notbold>214 posts<br><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Decent [3.45]</td><td valign=top class=mform width=100%><p><BLOCKQUOTE><b id=fs8>Quote:</b><hr size=1>but in PoP if you arent trying to maloxxxx and slow a mob as soon as it comes into range, you are doing something wrong.<hr size=1></BLOCKQUOTE><br><br>As with everything else, this will vary depending on what classes make up your group, but in general I highly disagree with this statement.&nbsp;&nbsp;If I were to try to slow a PoP mob as soon as it came within range I’d be a very dead shaman.  And even if I managed to survive, I’d piss off everyone else in the group and be kicked out if I continued doing so.  Unless you have someone in the group that can snare or otherwise totally tick off the mob, as soon as you cast on it YOU become its main target.  The groups I’m usually in have warriors as the main tanks.  I have to wait until at least 95% health to cast and usually 90% health.  Heck, if the mob has been pulled close to me and I send in my pup before 95% health the mob will sometimes come after me.  <br><br>Aggro control is a HUGE part of a successful group and especially a PoP group.  And I find it interesting as members come and go from our groups to see who has and who hasn’t learned this.  We hand a necromancer in our group last night who kept nuking as soon as the mob was pulled into camp in PoI.  Naturally the mob would come after him and he kept zoning.  That was one player we didn’t mind seeing leave.  Its no fun for the tanks to keep chasing after the mobs and its no fun for the healer to spend extra manna he wouldn’t have needed to if the caster had waited just a bit before casting.  If he had waited any longer to leave, our group leader would have removed him. <br><br>On the other hand, I used to group with a ranger that duel boxed with a cleric.  He snared everything he pulled and I could slow as soon as he pulled a mob without having to worry about being attacked.  And if I had to cast several times for the slow to stick and the mob did come after me, he would snare it again and all was well.  It’s a shame warriors can’t taunt well enough to do their job. But Sony seems to feel that warriors don’t need to hold aggro. *shrugs*  <br></p>&nbsp;<br><b>Pait Spiritwalker</b><br>Vah Shir Shaman, 62nd Season<br><b>Jondor</b><br>Barbarian Beastlord, 54th Season<br><br><b>Seventh Hammer</b> </td></td></tr>
